record.bridgyOriginalText:
usually, if i'm working with XML, it's generated, and i'm actually touching some DOM with code where i can directly insert text and attributes, so i never have to think about "character entities" and other such silly things. and, when i see </> in the serialized form, i think "ah. that's an escaped angle bracket, because in this language angle brackets are special". when looking at the text in an XML document, i'm thinking about those as just typographical symbols pointing in a direction, because when unescaped, that's basically their meaning. notably, i therefore think the abbreviations being < and > are stupid. they have the "wrong names" in my opinion. they're not comparison operators in XML!!!! (no i don't have any better suggestions; i don't think their names need to change; this opinion doesn't matter)

when writing XML stylesheets, i ended up writing an XPath expression like this: position() < last(). problem is, when embedding that in the actual stylesheet, that's not okay. you can't have "<" in an XML document.

<xsl:if test="position() < last()" />
this attribute is not well formed.

also, because XSL transformations are kind of, like, a "feature" of XML, right? and XPath is a standard supported by XML, i didn't really think of this as something that should generally need escaping. this is not "content" of the document. so i was initially a bit surprised that this doesn't parse; the quotes should delimit it fine, after all. and again, because i (a) always deal with XML from a DOM, and (b) didn't think of this as something "in" the document contents (even though the XPath queries absolutely are "in" the contents of the stylesheets, not merely part of their "structure"), and (c) don't generally think of the XML escape entities as encoding comparison operators (they relate to "angle brackets", which is different in my mind); i didn't immediately think to use those escape entities.

so i pondered. for a solid like 30 seconds or so. "how tf do i write this, then? does XPath have a synonym for this operator?". no, it doesn't have a synonym for it (lt is a different operator), but the spec explicitly warns about what i've just ran into, and notes that the < must be written as < in an XML document.
<xsl:if test="position() < last()" />
this seems obvious now (and it is obvious), but it was surprising enough to me because i always see < and think "that name is stupid". but here, the name is not stupid. when writing XPath expressions in XSL stylesheets, the "less than operator" is written <. i think this is the first time i've seen that mnemonic, and not immediately thought "that's not the correct name for this". it felt natural, for the first time ever.
